{{Infobox medical condition (new) | name = Baritosis | synonyms = | image = Ba-TableImage.png | caption = [[Barium]] | pronounce = | field = | symptoms = | complications = | onset = | duration = | types = | causes = | risks = | diagnosis = | differential = | prevention = | treatment = | medication = | prognosis = | frequency = | deaths = }} '''Baritosis''' is a [[benign]] type of [[pneumoconiosis]], which is caused by long-term exposure to [[barium]] dust.
Barium has a high radio-opacity and the disease may develop after few months of exposure. Extremely dense, discrete small [[opacities]] of 2–4&nbsp;mm diameter, sometimes of a star-like configuration, are seen on the [[radiograph]]. Their distribution is uniform. When they are very numerous, superimposition may give the impression of confluency, but this does not seem to occur in reality. The hilar [[lymph nodes]] can be very opaque but not enlarged. After cessation of exposure, there is a gradual clearing of the [[opacities]].
==Symptoms==
*[[Cough]] *[[Wheezing]] *Nasal [[irritation]]
In some cases, it is [[asymptomatic]].{{Citation needed|date=November 2009}} ==Diagnosis== The barium particles can be seen as opaque shadows on the chest [[X-ray]]s of people with baritosis. However, being a benign condition, it neither interferes with lung function nor causes symptoms other than a mild cough.
After exposure to barium dust ceases, the X-ray abnormalities gradually resolve.<ref name="pmid1257935">{{cite journal |author=Doig AT |title=Baritosis: a benign pneumoconiosis |journal=Thorax |volume=31 |issue=1 |pages=30–9 |date=February 1976 |pmid=1257935 |pmc=470358 |doi= 10.1136/thx.31.1.30|url=}}</ref> ==Treatment== {{Empty section|date=September 2017}}
