'''Psychiatry''' is the [[specialty (medicine)|medical specialty]] devoted to the diagnosis, prevention and treatment of [[mental disorder]]s.<ref>{{cite journal |title=First-year medical student objective structured clinical exam performance and specialty choice|last1=Backes|first1=Katherine A.|last2=Borges|first2=Nicole J.|last3=Binder|first3=S. Bruce |last4=Roman |first4=Brenda | name-list-format = vanc |year=2013|journal=International Journal of Medical Education|volume=4|pages=38–40|doi=10.5116/ijme.5103.b037}} {{open access}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |title=Psychiatry and Its Dichotomies|last=Alarcón|first=Renato D. | name-list-format = vanc |year=2016|journal=Psychiatric Times|volume=33|issue=5|page=1|doi=|url=http://www.psychiatrictimes.com/cultural-psychiatry/psychiatry-and-its-dichotomies}}</ref> These include various [[maladaptation]]s related to mood, behaviour, [[cognition]], and perceptions. See [[glossary of psychiatry]].

Initial psychiatric assessment of a person typically begins with a [[Medical history|case history]] and [[mental status examination]]. Physical examinations and [[Psychological testing|psychological tests]] may be conducted. On occasion, [[neuroimaging]] or other [[Neurophysiology|neurophysiological]] techniques are used.<ref name=NIMHSite/> Mental disorders are often diagnosed in accordance with clinical concepts listed in diagnostic manuals such as the ''[[International Classification of Diseases]]'' (ICD), edited and used by the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) and the widely used ''[[Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders]]'' (DSM), published by the [[American Psychiatric Association]] (APA). The fifth edition of the DSM ([[DSM-5]]) was published in 2013 which re-organized the larger categories of various diseases and expanded upon the previous edition to include information/insights that are consistent with current research.<ref name=Kupfer>{{cite journal | vauthors = Kupfer DJ, Regier DA | title = Why all of medicine should care about DSM-5 | journal = JAMA | volume = 303 | issue = 19 | pages = 1974–5 | date = May 2010 | pmid = 20483976 | doi = 10.1001/jama.2010.646 }}</ref>

<!-- Please see Talk page for discussion about the last paragraph of this lead section. -->
The combined treatment of [[psychiatric medication]] and [[psychotherapy]] has become the most common mode of psychiatric treatment in current practice,<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Gabbard GO | title = Psychotherapy in psychiatry | journal = International Review of Psychiatry | volume = 19 | issue = 1 | pages = 5–12 | date = February 2007 | pmid = 17365154 | pmc =  | doi = 10.1080/09540260601080813 }}</ref> but contemporary practice also includes a wide variety of other modalities, e.g., [[assertive community treatment]], [[Community reinforcement approach and family training|community reinforcement]], and [[supported employment]]. Treatment may be delivered on an [[inpatient]] or [[outpatient]] basis, depending on the severity of functional impairment or on other aspects of the disorder in question. An inpatient may be treated in a [[psychiatric hospital]]. Research and treatment within psychiatry as a whole are conducted on an interdisciplinary basis, e.g., with [[epidemiologists]], [[mental health counselor]]s, [[Nursing|nurses]], [[psychologists]], public health specialists, [[Radiology|radiologists]], and/or [[social workers]].

{{TOC limit|3}}

==Etymology==
[[File:American Lady Against The Sky.jpg|thumb|The word ''[[wiktionary:psyche|psyche]]'' comes from the [[ancient Greek]] for [[soul]] or [[butterfly]].<ref>{{cite magazine|last1=Rabuzzi|first1=Matthew|title=Butterfly Etymology|magazine=Cultural Entomology Digest|issue=4|url=http://www.insects.org/ced4/etymology.html|date=November 1997 |dead-url=yes |archive-date=3 December 1998 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/19981203024144/http://www.insects.org/ced4/etymology.html }}</ref> The fluttering insect appears in the [[coat of arms]] of Britain's [[Royal College of Psychiatrists]]<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = James FE | date = July 1991 | title = Psyche | journal = Psychiatric Bulletin|volume=15|issue=7|pages=429–31|url=http://pb.rcpsych.org/content/15/7/429 | doi = 10.1192/pb.15.7.429 | doi-access = free }}</ref>]]

The term "psychiatry" was first coined by the German [[physician]] [[Johann Christian Reil]] in 1808 and literally means the 'medical treatment of the soul' (''[[Wikt:psych|psych-]]'' "soul" from [[Ancient Greek]] ''psykhē'' "soul"; ''[[Wikt:-iatry|-iatry]]'' "medical treatment" from Gk. ''iātrikos'' "medical" from ''iāsthai'' "to heal"). A medical doctor specializing in psychiatry is a [[psychiatrist]]. (For a historical overview, see [[Timeline of psychiatry]].)

==Theory and focus==
{{quote box
| quote = "Psychiatry, more than any other branch of medicine, forces its practitioners to wrestle with the nature of evidence, the validity of introspection, problems in communication, and other long-standing philosophical issues" <small>([[Psychiatry#cite note-Guze4-5|Guze, 1992, p.4]]).</small>
| width = 24em
}}

Psychiatry refers to a field of medicine focused specifically on the [[mind]], aiming to [[Medical research|study]], [[Preventive healthcare|prevent]], and [[treatment of mental disorders|treat]] [[mental disorder]]s in [[human]]s.<ref name=Guze4>{{harvnb|Guze|1992|p=4}}.</ref><ref name=Storrow1>{{cite book |last=Storrow |first=Hugh A. | name-list-format = vanc |date=1969 |title=Outline of Clinical Psychiatry |location=New York |publisher=Appleton-Century-Crofts |page=1 |isbn=978-0-390-85075-1 |oclc=599349242 }}</ref>{{sfn|Lyness|1997|p=3}} It has been described as an intermediary between the world from a social context and the world from the perspective of those who are mentally ill.{{sfn|Gask|2004|p=7}}

People who specialize in psychiatry often differ from most other [[mental health professional]]s and [[physician]]s in that they must be familiar with both the [[social science|social]] and [[biology|biological sciences]].<ref name=Storrow1/> The discipline studies the operations of different organs and body systems as classified by the patient's subjective experiences and the objective physiology of the patient. {{sfn|Guze|1992|p=131}} Psychiatry treats mental disorders, which are conventionally divided into three very general categories: [[Mental disorder|mental illnesses]], severe learning disabilities, and [[personality disorder]]s.{{sfn|Gask|2004|p=113}} While the focus of psychiatry has changed little over time, the diagnostic and treatment processes have evolved dramatically and continue to do so. Since the late 20th century the field of psychiatry has continued to become more biological and less conceptually isolated from other medical fields.{{sfn|Gask|2004|p=128}}

