The '''Resal effect''' is a [[structural engineering]] term which refers to the way the [[compression (physics)|compressive force]] acting on a [[flange]] of a tapered [[beam (structure)|beam]] reduces the effective [[shear force]] acting on the beam.<ref name="Libby1990">{{cite book|author=James R. Libby|title=Modern Prestressed Concrete: Design Principles and Construction Methods|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zvylRLRBlUkC&pg=PA222|date=30 November 1990|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-0-442-31923-6|pages=222–3}}</ref><ref name="ChenDuan2014">{{cite book|author1=Wai-Fah Chen|author2=Lian Duan|title=Bridge Engineering Handbook, Second Edition: Superstructure Design|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DETNBQAAQBAJ&pg=PA227|date=24 January 2014|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-4398-5229-3|page=227}}</ref>

